# Literature Review: Incident-Specific Cyber Insurance

## Introduction

Incident-specific cyber insurance is a type of insurance product that offers coverage for losses arising from
various types of cyber incidents, such as data breaches and ransomware attacks. This coverage is provided
with separate limits and deductibles for each incident type, allowing buyers to customize their coverage
and manage sellers' risk exposures. However, the current market practice of offering a coverage bundle
for different incident types complicates the insurance process and raises several important questions. This
literature review aims to explore the existing research findings on incident-specific cyber insurance and
identify knowledge gaps that can guide future research in this area.

## Research Findings

### Coverage and Rate Analysis for Millimeter-Wave Cellular Networks

Bai and Heath (2014) conducted a coverage and rate analysis for millimeter-wave cellular networks.
Although this study is not directly related to incident-specific cyber insurance, it provides insights into
the analysis of coverage and rate in wireless networks. This research finding can be applied to evaluate
the coverage and performance of cyber insurance policies in different incident scenarios.

### 3-D Placement of an Unmanned Aerial Vehicle Base Station (UAV-BS) for Energy-Efficient Maximal

Coverage
Alzenad et al. (2017) investigated the 3-D placement of an unmanned aerial vehicle base station (UAV-BS)
for energy-efficient maximal coverage. While this research focuses on UAV placement, it offers valuable
insights into optimizing coverage and resource allocation. These findings can be applied to optimize the
placement of cyber insurance resources in different incident scenarios to maximize coverage and minimize
costs.

### On the coverage of LPWANs: range evaluation and channel attenuation model for LoRa technology

Petäjäjärvi et al. (2015) evaluated the coverage of low-power wide-area networks (LPWANs) and developed a channel attenuation model for LoRa technology. Although this research focuses on LPWANs,
it provides insights into coverage evaluation and modeling for wireless communication systems. These
findings can be used to evaluate and model the coverage of incident-specific cyber insurance policies in
different communication environments.
